WEBVTT

1
00:02:54,908 --> 00:02:56,324
Do you have any food?

2
00:02:58,904 --> 00:03:00,279
I'm very hungry.

3
00:03:22,671 --> 00:03:23,795
Let down your hair.

4
00:03:26,834 --> 00:03:28,416
You do not pass for a boy.

5
00:03:31,912 --> 00:03:33,370
Let down your hair.

6
00:03:44,941 --> 00:03:46,398
I am not afraid.

7
00:03:47,896 --> 00:03:49,767
Travelers spoke in these hills

8
00:03:49,769 --> 00:03:51,269
of the hero Robin Hood.

9
00:03:52,351 --> 00:03:53,765
He protects the meek.

10
00:04:01,799 --> 00:04:03,299
No one protects the meek.

11
00:04:05,379 --> 00:04:07,168
And he were no hero.

12
00:04:07,170 --> 00:04:10,621
He observed thrice a day
and gave silver to the poor.

13
00:04:10,623 --> 00:04:12,661
And he had the love
of Lady Marian.

14
00:04:12,663 --> 00:04:13,868
Is that not a hero?

15
00:04:13,870 --> 00:04:16,574
Lady Marian were taken
from an old shepherd's tale

16
00:04:16,576 --> 00:04:19,407
by a storyteller,
unfortunately, drunker than I.

17
00:04:20,448 --> 00:04:23,486
She were the great love
of Robin Hood.

18
00:04:24,070 --> 00:04:25,277
Mmm.

19
00:04:26,816 --> 00:04:29,480
There is no great love
for one such as him.

20
00:04:33,061 --> 00:04:34,390
I have known
those who met this man,

21
00:04:34,392 --> 00:04:36,266
would you like
to know a secret?

22
00:04:37,513 --> 00:04:38,554
I would.

23
00:04:39,928 --> 00:04:41,842
He never prayed once
in his life.

24
00:04:43,549 --> 00:04:46,212
These tales
spread across the land

25
00:04:46,214 --> 00:04:48,295
are lies upon lies.

26
00:04:49,793 --> 00:04:52,248
He were a murderous brigand,

27
00:04:52,250 --> 00:04:54,328
who perhaps cut the throat
of a sheriff

28
00:04:54,330 --> 00:04:56,493
in a long line of others.

29
00:04:56,495 --> 00:04:58,659
People saw a meaning
where there was none.

30
00:05:00,117 --> 00:05:02,030
He was not a hero.

31
00:05:02,032 --> 00:05:04,153
He robbed and killed
for the joy of it,

32
00:05:04,155 --> 00:05:05,403
nothing more.

33
00:05:11,064 --> 00:05:12,312
Those you met...

34
00:05:14,269 --> 00:05:15,765
did they say he felt remorse

35
00:05:15,767 --> 00:05:16,849
for his crimes?

36
00:05:21,096 --> 00:05:23,094
I suspect he felt tired.

37
00:05:26,340 --> 00:05:29,960
I would say if you met
this villain Robin Hood,

38
00:05:29,962 --> 00:05:31,126
you should make haste away

39
00:05:31,128 --> 00:05:33,333
and keep whatever life
you have left here.

40
00:06:02,845 --> 00:06:06,467
...pardon of our sins.

41
00:06:08,298 --> 00:06:10,172
Through Jesus Christ our Lord.

42
00:06:11,794 --> 00:06:14,168
Amen.

43
00:07:19,894 --> 00:07:21,516
Who was your kin?

44
00:07:24,015 --> 00:07:26,468
William Wainwright...

45
00:07:26,470 --> 00:07:28,468
...of Pickering.

46
00:07:29,010 --> 00:07:30,383
Pickering?

47
00:07:32,297 --> 00:07:33,668
Father?

48
00:07:35,128 --> 00:07:36,377
Grandfather?

49
00:07:41,830 --> 00:07:44,158
You should have bathed,

50
00:07:44,160 --> 00:07:45,826
or waited for the wind
to change.

51
00:07:48,572 --> 00:07:50,654
Or kept your weight
on your back foot.

52
00:07:53,027 --> 00:07:54,524
That's all.

53
00:07:55,025 --> 00:07:56,273
You did well.

54
00:09:17,192 --> 00:09:18,650
They sing lies.

55
00:09:20,023 --> 00:09:21,772
These foolish common folk.

56
00:09:23,395 --> 00:09:26,142
Lies of his heroism
and goodness.

57
00:09:28,181 --> 00:09:29,722
But blood debts are owed.

58
00:09:31,428 --> 00:09:34,134
And generations
of his victims hunt him.

59
00:09:36,090 --> 00:09:37,297
For in truth...

60
00:09:38,963 --> 00:09:41,625
none were more wicked
and wanton

61
00:09:41,627 --> 00:09:44,290
than the murderous bandit
Robin Hood...

62
00:09:46,080 --> 00:09:47,704
and his Little John.

63
00:09:52,074 --> 00:09:53,323
Speak to Thomas.

64
00:09:54,947 --> 00:09:57,525
He were hanged in the South.

65
00:09:57,527 --> 00:09:58,486
Will?

66
00:10:00,024 --> 00:10:01,441
They gutted him.

67
00:10:03,146 --> 00:10:04,770
I have no one else to ask.

68
00:10:07,059 --> 00:10:08,308
What happened?

69
00:10:09,099 --> 00:10:12,262
My name is Edward.

70
00:10:13,095 --> 00:10:14,552
Who was Edward?

71
00:10:16,133 --> 00:10:19,421
I met him on the road,
ten summers ago.

72
00:10:19,423 --> 00:10:22,042
His brother died.
And he were going to grow

73
00:10:22,044 --> 00:10:24,084
rye and peas
on his brother's land.

74
00:10:26,123 --> 00:10:27,831
No one knew Edward's face.

75
00:10:29,537 --> 00:10:30,661
So I killed him.

76
00:10:31,951 --> 00:10:33,283
Now I am Edward.

77
00:10:34,782 --> 00:10:36,323
And Margaret's a good wife.

78
00:10:37,196 --> 00:10:38,446
It's a good farm.

79
00:10:39,527 --> 00:10:40,693
What happened?

80
00:10:42,149 --> 00:10:44,064
A family on the land
found me out.

81
00:10:44,897 --> 00:10:48,099
Took my farm.
Took my Margaret.

82
00:10:48,101 --> 00:10:49,559
Tried to take my life.

83
00:10:53,096 --> 00:10:55,092
I cannot take back alone
what is mine.

84
00:10:55,094 --> 00:10:56,428
It's not yours.

85
00:10:58,426 --> 00:10:59,715
It's my family.

86
00:11:04,959 --> 00:11:06,293
I'm tired, John.

87
00:11:07,874 --> 00:11:09,290
Edward.

88
00:11:11,703 --> 00:11:13,076
I'm tired, Edward.

89
00:11:17,240 --> 00:11:21,068
It would be
a mighty battle.

90
00:11:21,693 --> 00:11:23,108
One for the stories.

91
00:11:29,228 --> 00:11:30,766
They are strong?

92
00:11:30,768 --> 00:11:31,767
Aye.

93
00:11:32,931 --> 00:11:35,094
They come from an old family.

94
00:11:35,096 --> 00:11:36,595
They say from Viking blood.

95
00:11:38,427 --> 00:11:40,756
There's a story
that once their elderfather

96
00:11:40,758 --> 00:11:41,757
fought a bear.

97
00:11:43,546 --> 00:11:46,127
It would be
a mighty battle, Robin.

98
00:11:49,082 --> 00:11:50,332
How many are there?

99
00:11:51,705 --> 00:11:53,661
Four? Five?

100
00:11:54,161 --> 00:11:55,743
Together we can best them.

101
00:11:59,198 --> 00:12:00,571
We'll likely die.

102
00:12:07,190 --> 00:12:12,724
♪ As I was walking all alone ♪

103
00:12:12,726 --> 00:12:18,009
♪ I heard two crows
a-making a moan ♪

104
00:12:18,011 --> 00:12:23,796
♪ One said to the other,
did say-o ♪

105
00:12:23,798 --> 00:12:28,292
♪ "Where shall we go
and dine today-o? ♪

106
00:12:28,294 --> 00:12:34,035
♪ "Where shall we go
and dine today?" ♪

107
00:12:34,037 --> 00:12:38,449
♪ In behind
that old turf wall ♪

108
00:12:38,451 --> 00:12:43,693
♪ I sense there lies
a new slain knight ♪

109
00:12:43,695 --> 00:12:49,396
♪ And nobody knows
that he lies there-o ♪

110
00:12:49,398 --> 00:12:53,848
♪ But his hawk, and his hound
and his lady fair-o ♪

111
00:12:53,850 --> 00:12:58,264
♪ His hawk, and his hound
and his lady fair ♪

112
00:13:05,963 --> 00:13:11,457
♪ Many a one for him
shall moan ♪

113
00:13:11,459 --> 00:13:16,660
♪ None shall know
where he has gone ♪

114
00:13:16,662 --> 00:13:23,362
♪ O'er his white bones,
when they are bare-o ♪

115
00:13:23,364 --> 00:13:28,399
♪ Wind shall blow
for evermore-o ♪

116
00:13:28,401 --> 00:13:33,354
♪ Wind shall blow
for evermore ♪

117
00:13:35,102 --> 00:13:36,268
Robin!

118
00:13:38,057 --> 00:13:39,306
Robin!

119
00:13:40,928 --> 00:13:43,261
Bread?

120
00:13:45,092 --> 00:13:46,507
This is a good adventure.

121
00:13:48,588 --> 00:13:49,629
A good adventure.

122
00:13:53,126 --> 00:13:56,162
You remember
when we met the potter,

123
00:13:56,164 --> 00:13:59,243
did we leave him naked
or did we kill him?

124
00:13:59,245 --> 00:14:01,116
Oh, I tried to tell the story

125
00:14:01,118 --> 00:14:03,241
and someone said
we left him naked.

126
00:14:03,698 --> 00:14:05,072
But I couldn't remember.

127
00:14:05,988 --> 00:14:07,860
You always told
it well, Robin.

128
00:14:09,942 --> 00:14:11,523
Why would we leave him naked?

129
00:14:13,064 --> 00:14:14,271
I don't know.

130
00:14:16,144 --> 00:14:17,559
It were a jest.

131
00:14:18,891 --> 00:14:20,182
We never met a potter.

132
00:14:21,098 --> 00:14:23,052
What do you mean
we never met him?

133
00:14:23,054 --> 00:14:24,259
I mean,
that never happened.

134
00:14:24,261 --> 00:14:26,384
It's just a story
you heard somewhere.

135
00:14:28,923 --> 00:14:30,297
But if we did meet
a potter,

136
00:14:31,503 --> 00:14:32,875
we killed him.

137
00:14:32,877 --> 00:14:34,789
I'd remember
if it were a story.

138
00:14:34,791 --> 00:14:36,747
Here!

139
00:14:37,207 --> 00:14:38,621
Tell me about your wife.

140
00:14:41,535 --> 00:14:42,617
Margaret.

141
00:14:44,698 --> 00:14:46,528
She's a good woman.

142
00:14:46,530 --> 00:14:50,275
She's a very good woman.
She's pious.

143
00:14:50,277 --> 00:14:52,190
She teaches me prayerfulness.

144
00:14:52,192 --> 00:14:53,441
Paint a portrait.

145
00:14:55,272 --> 00:14:56,562
Paint a portrait?

146
00:14:58,019 --> 00:15:00,599
Paint a portrait?

147
00:15:05,095 --> 00:15:09,632
She has hair that's red.

148
00:15:10,299 --> 00:15:11,920
Red like?

149
00:15:11,922 --> 00:15:14,126
Red like fresh blood.

150
00:15:14,128 --> 00:15:16,291
No, not blood.
No, no, no.

151
00:15:16,293 --> 00:15:19,123
Something that's red
and that's good, like her.

152
00:15:20,205 --> 00:15:21,828
Red like... I don't know.

153
00:15:25,908 --> 00:15:27,363
Like the setting sun.

154
00:15:27,365 --> 00:15:31,069
Aye, like
the setting summer sun.

155
00:15:32,443 --> 00:15:34,897
Margaret's a good wife.

156
00:15:34,899 --> 00:15:38,062
With hair that's red
like the setting summer sun.

157
00:15:39,935 --> 00:15:41,226
She cares for me.

158
00:15:42,724 --> 00:15:43,765
And I care for her.

159
00:15:48,885 --> 00:15:49,842
Hmm.

160
00:15:52,423 --> 00:15:56,211
Robin, there are open
lands past the mountains.

161
00:15:58,376 --> 00:16:00,165
Many places to begin again.

162
00:16:05,160 --> 00:16:07,200
No, I do not aim
to begin again.

163
00:16:12,694 --> 00:16:14,318
I aim for a right death.

164
00:17:55,591 --> 00:17:56,963
Edward!

165
00:17:56,965 --> 00:17:58,087
Go, Hendrie!

166
00:17:58,089 --> 00:17:59,835
Edward!

167
00:17:59,837 --> 00:18:02,210
Go, Hendrie, run! Now!

168
00:18:02,709 --> 00:18:04,457
-Edward!
-Back!

169
00:18:04,459 --> 00:18:06,498
Hendrie, get the others!

170
00:18:07,163 --> 00:18:08,455
Edward!

171
00:18:09,412 --> 00:18:12,075
Edward, my love...

172
00:18:13,450 --> 00:18:15,320
Watch over Little Margaret.

173
00:20:09,957 --> 00:20:13,203
Little one, don't worry.

174
00:20:13,205 --> 00:20:16,906
Don't worry.
Come here, come here.

175
00:20:16,908 --> 00:20:19,530
You're safe.
You're safe, daughter.

176
00:20:23,444 --> 00:20:25,691
Let us pray. Let us pray.

177
00:20:27,939 --> 00:20:30,934
O Lord, our God,

178
00:20:30,936 --> 00:20:34,765
grant us grace to desire Thee
with our whole heart.

179
00:20:35,349 --> 00:20:37,428
Come on now, pray.

180
00:20:37,430 --> 00:20:40,591
And in finding Thee,
we may love Thee.

181
00:20:40,593 --> 00:20:43,546
And in loving Thee,
we may hate those sins

182
00:20:43,548 --> 00:20:46,253
from which Thou hast
redeemed us.

183
00:20:46,255 --> 00:20:49,294
For the sake of Jesus Christ.
Amen.

184
00:20:51,250 --> 00:20:54,329
Yes. Yes, good.

185
00:20:54,330 --> 00:20:57,244
Good.

186
00:22:03,220 --> 00:22:04,426
I'm sorry.

187
00:22:06,466 --> 00:22:07,506
I'm sorry.

188
00:22:10,544 --> 00:22:11,627
I'm sorry.

189
00:22:13,168 --> 00:22:15,415
It were that when I woke.

190
00:22:17,787 --> 00:22:19,411
It were that when I woke.

191
00:22:20,659 --> 00:22:22,241
Cousin.

192
00:22:22,242 --> 00:22:24,240
It were that when I woke.

193
00:22:25,738 --> 00:22:27,154
I'm sorry.

194
00:22:28,526 --> 00:22:33,644
♪ The wind
between the north and east ♪

195
00:22:33,646 --> 00:22:37,227
♪ Blowed every chill
and cold ♪

196
00:22:39,059 --> 00:22:43,634
♪ Or coldly blowed to me,
at least ♪

197
00:22:43,636 --> 00:22:47,093
♪ My clothes were thin
and old ♪

198
00:22:48,133 --> 00:22:52,834
♪ The grass all dropping wet
with dew ♪

199
00:22:52,836 --> 00:22:55,583
♪ Low bent their tiny spears ♪

200
00:22:56,999 --> 00:23:01,162
♪ The lowly daisy bended too ♪

201
00:23:01,994 --> 00:23:06,738
♪ More lowly with my tears ♪

202
00:23:09,029 --> 00:23:14,107
♪ Oh, luckless youth
to sorrow born ♪

203
00:23:14,815 --> 00:23:17,519
♪ Shun'd son of poverty ♪

204
00:23:19,144 --> 00:23:23,721
♪ The world made gamely
sport and scorn ♪

205
00:23:24,430 --> 00:23:26,760
♪ And grinning infamy ♪

206
00:23:28,259 --> 00:23:32,336
♪ Unequalled though
my sorrow seems ♪

207
00:23:32,338 --> 00:23:35,792
♪ But great indeed they are ♪

208
00:23:35,794 --> 00:23:39,664
♪ Oh hear my sorrows
for my stream ♪

209
00:23:40,955 --> 00:23:45,159
♪ You'll find an equal there ♪

210
00:23:46,573 --> 00:23:50,195
♪ The land and Eddings
are no more ♪

211
00:23:51,278 --> 00:23:54,233
♪ The pastures too are gone ♪

212
00:23:56,065 --> 00:24:00,892
♪ The greens, the meadows
and the moors ♪

213
00:24:00,894 --> 00:24:03,596
♪ Are all cut up and gone ♪

214
00:24:03,598 --> 00:24:05,847
We cry
to Thee, O Lord.

215
00:24:07,470 --> 00:24:10,093
Do Thou have mercy upon us?

216
00:24:11,383 --> 00:24:13,379
And grant forgiveness.

217
00:24:13,381 --> 00:24:17,500
O King of heaven,
and everlasting Lord,

218
00:24:17,501 --> 00:24:21,538
receive our prayers
which we pour forth.

219
00:24:22,997 --> 00:24:24,826
And grant forgiveness.

220
00:24:24,828 --> 00:24:29,488
Visit the sick,
bring forth the captive,

221
00:24:29,490 --> 00:24:33,070
help the widow and the orphan.

222
00:24:34,401 --> 00:24:36,939
And grant forgiveness.

223
00:24:36,941 --> 00:24:42,059
We have sinned
and departed from Thee.

224
00:24:42,061 --> 00:24:47,347
Wilt Thou, the Redeemer
of all, save us?

225
00:24:48,387 --> 00:24:50,383
And grant forgiveness.

226
00:24:50,385 --> 00:24:53,297
Have mercy on the penitent

227
00:24:53,299 --> 00:24:57,462
and wash away
the stains of sin.

228
00:24:59,126 --> 00:25:01,249
And grant forgiveness.

229
00:25:02,915 --> 00:25:04,663
Amen.

230
00:25:50,075 --> 00:25:51,574
Kill him!

231
00:25:58,734 --> 00:26:00,065
Godwyn!

232
00:26:36,029 --> 00:26:37,526
No!

233
00:28:04,234 --> 00:28:07,020
No. Please. Please.

234
00:28:07,022 --> 00:28:10,100
Please, please!

235
00:28:40,198 --> 00:28:43,109
- Margaret? Margaret!
- No, no.

236
00:28:43,111 --> 00:28:45,065
No!

237
00:28:47,316 --> 00:28:49,646
John! Don't!

238
00:28:54,932 --> 00:28:57,264
Little John!

239
00:29:04,299 --> 00:29:08,792
Twenty winters ago,
you murdered my cousin,

240
00:29:08,794 --> 00:29:10,709
Walter of Hathersage.

241
00:29:12,124 --> 00:29:14,993
You have murdered my sons

242
00:29:14,995 --> 00:29:16,619
and my grandson.

243
00:29:17,660 --> 00:29:18,908
As wergild...

244
00:29:19,367 --> 00:29:22,362
I accept your life...

245
00:29:22,364 --> 00:29:25,359
and the life of your daughter.

246
00:31:33,025 --> 00:31:34,565
...heinous crimes...

247
00:31:36,646 --> 00:31:40,268
...slayer of man,
woman and child...

248
00:31:47,676 --> 00:31:49,301
No...

249
00:31:54,795 --> 00:31:56,500
No...

250
00:31:56,501 --> 00:32:00,828
No! No!
No! No! No!

251
00:32:00,830 --> 00:32:02,661
No!

252
00:32:03,660 --> 00:32:05,451
No!

253
00:33:15,797 --> 00:33:17,088
Robin?

254
00:33:18,045 --> 00:33:21,375
I've heard stories
of a Priory hidden away.

255
00:33:22,957 --> 00:33:24,370
There's a Prioress there

256
00:33:24,372 --> 00:33:26,495
who's older
than anyone remembers...

257
00:33:27,910 --> 00:33:29,451
she has healing magic.

258
00:33:30,949 --> 00:33:32,695
I'll take you to her.

259
00:33:32,697 --> 00:33:34,528
She'll get you well again.

260
00:33:35,486 --> 00:33:37,567
I've heard incredible stories.

261
00:34:38,382 --> 00:34:41,295
Robin, we must leave you.

262
00:34:42,793 --> 00:34:44,126
They'll be hunting us.

263
00:35:21,005 --> 00:35:22,463
Look at the snow...

264
00:35:25,460 --> 00:35:27,291
it's strange
for it to fall this late.

265
00:35:31,413 --> 00:35:33,243
But it won't stay
on the ground...

266
00:35:36,366 --> 00:35:38,197
and the long days
will soon some.

267
00:36:31,019 --> 00:36:32,434
A man brought you here.

268
00:36:33,974 --> 00:36:35,429
He sealed
your wounds with fire

269
00:36:35,431 --> 00:36:37,471
and he did not do a poor job.

270
00:36:39,052 --> 00:36:40,634
You have been here six days.

271
00:36:42,133 --> 00:36:43,839
You have wounds
in your abdomen.

272
00:36:44,921 --> 00:36:47,295
Ribs and a leg badly broken.

273
00:36:49,376 --> 00:36:51,374
Do you understand my words?

274
00:36:55,619 --> 00:36:57,573
Where is this?

275
00:36:57,575 --> 00:36:59,821
You're at
the Priory of St. Clement.

276
00:36:59,823 --> 00:37:01,240
We're a place for you to heal.

277
00:37:02,197 --> 00:37:03,819
Wha... What town?

278
00:37:04,818 --> 00:37:06,151
There is no town.

279
00:37:07,898 --> 00:37:09,646
Do you know the story of Saul?

280
00:37:11,769 --> 00:37:13,100
What?

281
00:37:13,102 --> 00:37:16,264
It goes, there once
was a man, Saul...

282
00:37:16,266 --> 00:37:19,595
a breather of menaces
against disciples of the Lord.

283
00:37:20,428 --> 00:37:22,258
He came
to the Prince of Priests

284
00:37:22,260 --> 00:37:24,671
and asked of him
letters into Damascus,

285
00:37:24,673 --> 00:37:26,087
to the synagogues.

286
00:37:26,089 --> 00:37:27,461
That if he came across

287
00:37:27,463 --> 00:37:29,375
any man or woman of this life,
he should lead them bound

288
00:37:29,377 --> 00:37:30,750
and...

289
00:37:32,167 --> 00:37:34,165
That is all we need to do.

290
00:37:35,289 --> 00:37:36,828
Just a few drops.

291
00:37:39,367 --> 00:37:41,158
It was not too painful?

292
00:37:43,198 --> 00:37:44,446
It were not.

293
00:37:48,941 --> 00:37:50,232
I'm Sister Brigid.

294
00:37:51,646 --> 00:37:53,063
What's your name?

295
00:37:54,935 --> 00:37:56,143
Randolph.

296
00:38:00,430 --> 00:38:03,094
Well, I owe you
an apology, Randolph.

297
00:38:03,926 --> 00:38:05,425
What apology?

298
00:38:07,381 --> 00:38:09,296
You begged for me
to let you die.

299
00:38:11,294 --> 00:38:12,583
And I did not.

300
00:38:14,956 --> 00:38:16,038
You said it was right.

301
00:38:16,040 --> 00:38:17,288
I were with fever.

302
00:38:19,327 --> 00:38:21,118
Well, your fever has passed.

303
00:38:22,698 --> 00:38:23,781
Rest now, Randolph.

304
00:38:47,341 --> 00:38:50,463
Your body
is covered in scars.

305
00:39:07,528 --> 00:39:09,860
Do you mean anyone
at this Priory harm?

306
00:39:13,898 --> 00:39:15,106
I do not.

307
00:39:25,303 --> 00:39:28,342
Will any harm
follow you here?

308
00:39:30,174 --> 00:39:31,464
It will not.

309
00:39:40,620 --> 00:39:43,534
You will do them no harm.

310
00:40:15,627 --> 00:40:17,791
Now back to the bed.

311
00:40:32,944 --> 00:40:34,359
Now back to the door.

312
00:41:02,456 --> 00:41:03,703
Now open the door.

313
00:41:22,936 --> 00:41:24,516
Go as far as you'd like.

314
00:43:12,326 --> 00:43:14,239
William,
careful, please.

315
00:43:22,400 --> 00:43:23,607
Can you row yet?

316
00:43:26,438 --> 00:43:28,558
There is a boat
on the west shore.

317
00:43:31,015 --> 00:43:32,264
That's all right.

318
00:43:33,597 --> 00:43:36,092
You can stay here
if you help in the orchard.

319
00:43:36,094 --> 00:43:38,092
Oh, I'm... not a farmer.

320
00:43:38,966 --> 00:43:40,590
Then you know not how to hunt.

321
00:43:41,172 --> 00:43:42,629
Aye, I know how to hunt.

322
00:43:43,961 --> 00:43:46,832
There is some game
on this island.

323
00:43:46,834 --> 00:43:50,454
But no, you cannot hunt.
You cannot even draw a bow.

324
00:43:50,456 --> 00:43:52,701
-I can draw my bow.
-It's mostly rabbits.

325
00:43:52,703 --> 00:43:55,451
-Do you know how to trap?
-I know how to trap.

326
00:43:57,114 --> 00:43:59,277
Good. But no more
than six traps

327
00:43:59,279 --> 00:44:01,277
or the population
will not sustain.

328
00:44:01,984 --> 00:44:03,525
Can you manage six traps?

329
00:44:07,937 --> 00:44:09,395
I can manage six traps.

330
00:44:11,642 --> 00:44:12,683
Good.

331
00:44:13,972 --> 00:44:16,845
Then the rest of your time,
you may help in the orchard.

332
00:44:53,226 --> 00:44:54,766
Are you
trying to flee?

333
00:44:58,927 --> 00:45:00,219
You are quiet.

334
00:45:01,966 --> 00:45:04,131
I am quiet
and slow.

335
00:45:05,464 --> 00:45:09,040
You are quiet,
but you need to be slow.

336
00:45:09,042 --> 00:45:10,207
You're a cripple.

337
00:45:10,209 --> 00:45:11,914
Aye, you're a leper.

338
00:45:12,831 --> 00:45:16,575
It is all right
to be slow. We are safe here.

339
00:45:16,577 --> 00:45:19,240
That's quite a thing
to say. You know that?

340
00:45:19,242 --> 00:45:21,321
I know that
because she has made us safe.

341
00:45:21,323 --> 00:45:22,696
Oh, your Prioress?

342
00:45:25,110 --> 00:45:26,401
She were like us.

343
00:45:27,400 --> 00:45:31,480
She knew great sorrow.
Great pain.

344
00:45:32,229 --> 00:45:33,478
Widowed young.

345
00:45:35,683 --> 00:45:37,222
But through that sorrow,

346
00:45:37,224 --> 00:45:39,428
she found the strength
to heal us.

347
00:45:39,430 --> 00:45:42,049
Well, you do not look
like you've been healed.

348
00:45:45,466 --> 00:45:47,295
The Prioress once told me
a story

349
00:45:47,297 --> 00:45:49,295
of a great philosopher...

350
00:45:50,419 --> 00:45:53,083
the greatest philosopher
of his time.

351
00:45:54,039 --> 00:45:57,452
But one day,
his king turned against him.

352
00:45:57,454 --> 00:46:00,533
Threw him in a dungeon
to be tortured and executed.

353
00:46:01,989 --> 00:46:04,070
But in his misery,

354
00:46:04,072 --> 00:46:07,192
when he had nothing,
an angel came

355
00:46:07,194 --> 00:46:09,442
to the philosopher
and she spoke to him.

356
00:46:10,565 --> 00:46:12,437
And from her,

357
00:46:12,439 --> 00:46:15,059
he learned
that it did not matter

358
00:46:15,061 --> 00:46:17,641
if this whole world
were misery...

359
00:46:19,390 --> 00:46:21,430
if all he had were death.

360
00:46:23,094 --> 00:46:25,132
Because he had one thing

361
00:46:25,134 --> 00:46:27,465
that could never be
touched or taken.

362
00:46:30,046 --> 00:46:31,378
He had his mind.

363
00:46:33,209 --> 00:46:34,458
And in his mind...

364
00:46:36,165 --> 00:46:37,497
he had God.

365
00:46:40,161 --> 00:46:43,698
It's never too late
to find peace.

366
00:46:44,656 --> 00:46:45,736
What are you doing?

367
00:46:45,738 --> 00:46:48,691
Ah,
I row across every day.

368
00:46:48,693 --> 00:46:50,606
Your friend was strong enough
to take you,

369
00:46:50,608 --> 00:46:52,521
but some are not,
so I ferry them.

370
00:46:52,523 --> 00:46:55,435
-Will you take me across?
-I will not.

371
00:46:55,437 --> 00:46:58,556
You can row yourself
when you're stronger.

372
00:46:58,558 --> 00:47:01,429
For now, work at your tasks.
Trapping, I hear.

373
00:47:01,431 --> 00:47:03,678
-I will hunt.
-No, you can't hunt.

374
00:47:09,090 --> 00:47:10,711
Leper,

375
00:47:10,713 --> 00:47:13,128
what happened
to that great philosopher?

376
00:47:14,127 --> 00:47:17,124
He were tortured
and executed, of course.

377
00:47:18,622 --> 00:47:19,662
Of course.

378
00:47:26,448 --> 00:47:29,026
♪ Sumer is icumen
In loude sing cuccu! ♪

379
00:47:29,028 --> 00:47:31,399
♪ Groweth seed
and bloweth meed ♪

380
00:47:31,401 --> 00:47:33,563
♪ And springth the wode now ♪

381
00:47:33,565 --> 00:47:35,727
♪ Sing cuccu ♪

382
00:47:35,729 --> 00:47:39,100
♪ Ewe bleteth after lamb
Loweth after calve cow ♪

383
00:49:20,209 --> 00:49:22,497
Oi! Oi!

384
00:49:22,499 --> 00:49:24,537
The Leper has brought someone!

385
00:49:24,954 --> 00:49:26,702
From the far shore!

386
00:50:06,496 --> 00:50:07,828
Papa's dead.

387
00:51:23,585 --> 00:51:25,126
How's the girl?

388
00:51:38,363 --> 00:51:40,361
Let me show you
my trees.

389
00:51:50,435 --> 00:51:53,636
These are the elderberries.

390
00:51:53,638 --> 00:51:56,427
They harvest
late in the summer.

391
00:51:56,429 --> 00:51:58,715
Do they know
what you were before this?

392
00:51:58,717 --> 00:52:00,921
Oh, you'll have
to favor this side

393
00:52:00,923 --> 00:52:02,089
for my hearing.

394
00:52:04,421 --> 00:52:07,167
Pears, I harvest just after.

395
00:52:10,247 --> 00:52:12,328
And what were I before this?

396
00:52:12,330 --> 00:52:14,075
Oh,
a sellsword at best.

397
00:52:14,077 --> 00:52:16,450
Aye, at best, certainly.

398
00:52:17,366 --> 00:52:18,738
We have a way about us!

399
00:52:20,196 --> 00:52:21,692
You remember the trees?

400
00:52:21,694 --> 00:52:24,150
- Pears and elderberries.
- Wonderful.

401
00:52:27,064 --> 00:52:28,355
Some of them know.

402
00:52:29,561 --> 00:52:32,766
But the Prioress does not care
who we were.

403
00:52:34,972 --> 00:52:37,429
And the apples harvest
in the autumn.

404
00:52:38,718 --> 00:52:41,799
Did she, uh,
speak of what happened to her?

405
00:52:43,464 --> 00:52:45,543
Well, the Prioress
is tending to the girl.

406
00:52:45,545 --> 00:52:48,418
You should speak with her,
if you are concerned.

407
00:52:51,914 --> 00:52:53,163
What were the trees?

408
00:52:54,994 --> 00:52:57,409
Pears, apples
and elderberries.

409
00:52:59,324 --> 00:53:00,530
Wonderful.

410
00:53:12,270 --> 00:53:14,100
This will be
your last letting.

411
00:53:15,432 --> 00:53:17,638
Though your body
still has much healing.

412
00:53:21,509 --> 00:53:22,591
You're tired.

413
00:53:23,798 --> 00:53:24,839
I am.

414
00:53:26,130 --> 00:53:27,628
But I have been tired before.

415
00:53:29,834 --> 00:53:31,251
The child does not sleep.

416
00:53:34,787 --> 00:53:36,162
What happened to her?

417
00:53:37,784 --> 00:53:38,825
Terrible things.

418
00:53:42,072 --> 00:53:45,276
-She told you her story?
-No, she does not speak.

419
00:53:45,278 --> 00:53:47,524
She does not eat
and she does not sleep.

420
00:53:55,101 --> 00:53:56,433
What is her name?

421
00:54:04,092 --> 00:54:05,341
Margaret.

422
00:54:08,463 --> 00:54:09,752
Who is she?

423
00:54:11,834 --> 00:54:14,747
I met her father. A farmer.

424
00:54:15,996 --> 00:54:17,784
Well,
he's dead.

425
00:54:17,786 --> 00:54:18,866
It seems.

426
00:54:18,868 --> 00:54:20,324
And the mother?

427
00:54:20,326 --> 00:54:23,197
-Ah, I think dead.
-How?

428
00:54:23,199 --> 00:54:25,280
I don't know. Dead past.

429
00:54:26,445 --> 00:54:27,444
Slain?

430
00:54:28,692 --> 00:54:29,732
Perhaps.

431
00:54:35,145 --> 00:54:36,517
You lie very well.

432
00:54:45,966 --> 00:54:47,258
Did the child see?

433
00:54:49,879 --> 00:54:51,336
She could have.

434
00:54:53,917 --> 00:54:55,665
That is much
for a child to see.

435
00:55:05,863 --> 00:55:07,320
I'm sorry for your friend.

436
00:55:11,899 --> 00:55:13,107
Thank you.

437
00:55:14,355 --> 00:55:16,560
Would you like me
to pray for him?

438
00:55:20,765 --> 00:55:22,181
As you wish.

439
00:55:25,718 --> 00:55:26,842
What was his name?

440
00:55:31,504 --> 00:55:32,586
Edward.

441
00:55:34,834 --> 00:55:36,126
Edward.

442
00:55:39,247 --> 00:55:40,826
Be not your heart afraid,

443
00:55:40,828 --> 00:55:42,076
for ye believe in God

444
00:55:42,078 --> 00:55:43,409
and ye believe in me.

445
00:55:45,324 --> 00:55:48,155
In the house of my father,
there are many rooms.

446
00:55:49,445 --> 00:55:52,522
And when I make ready
for you a place,

447
00:55:52,524 --> 00:55:54,856
I shall come
and take thee to myself.

448
00:55:56,230 --> 00:55:59,227
For where I am,
He may be also.

449
00:56:01,599 --> 00:56:03,805
And whither I go,
He shall know the way.

450
00:56:24,910 --> 00:56:26,780
- She has a knife.
- Margaret!

451
00:56:26,782 --> 00:56:28,196
She stabbed me!

452
00:56:28,198 --> 00:56:29,696
Margaret!

453
00:56:32,028 --> 00:56:34,066
It's all right.

454
00:56:35,232 --> 00:56:37,437
Margaret, it's...
it's all right.

455
00:56:37,439 --> 00:56:39,312
Margaret, it's all right.

456
00:56:42,267 --> 00:56:43,972
She don't know
this island.

457
00:56:43,974 --> 00:56:45,680
There are boar about.

458
00:56:48,718 --> 00:56:50,299
- Margaret!
- Margaret!

459
00:56:50,301 --> 00:56:52,131
Margaret!

460
00:56:52,133 --> 00:56:55,045
- Margaret!
- Margaret!

461
00:56:55,047 --> 00:56:56,585
Margaret!

462
00:58:42,105 --> 00:58:43,313
Oi.

463
00:58:45,894 --> 00:58:46,935
Oi!

464
00:58:55,592 --> 00:58:56,758
Give it.

465
00:59:10,161 --> 00:59:11,410
Give it.

466
00:59:28,768 --> 00:59:30,432
Those men that hurt you,

467
00:59:33,721 --> 00:59:34,762
do they know you're here?

468
00:59:40,506 --> 00:59:41,505
Hmm.

469
00:59:48,248 --> 00:59:49,622
What's my name?

470
00:59:55,782 --> 00:59:56,781
Say my name.

471
00:59:58,987 --> 01:00:00,236
Randolph.

472
01:00:05,939 --> 01:00:07,187
That's right.

473
01:00:12,349 --> 01:00:14,097
Who's Little John?

474
01:00:16,303 --> 01:00:19,590
That name is nonsense
and you should never speak it.

475
01:00:19,592 --> 01:00:22,212
And if you speak it,
a cat will come in the night

476
01:00:22,214 --> 01:00:23,336
and take your tongue.

477
01:00:33,744 --> 01:00:34,827
It's all right.

478
01:00:37,907 --> 01:00:39,113
Go to sleep.

479
01:00:46,441 --> 01:00:47,772
I'll watch the storm.

480
01:00:52,184 --> 01:00:54,265
All right, lay down.

481
01:00:58,094 --> 01:00:59,344
Close your eyes.

482
01:01:04,547 --> 01:01:05,587
You can sleep.

483
01:01:10,832 --> 01:01:12,122
Sleep.

484
01:01:50,542 --> 01:01:52,707
Thank you
for bringing her back.

485
01:01:55,079 --> 01:01:56,329
It were nothing.

486
01:02:01,656 --> 01:02:03,738
Do you know the story
of this Priory?

487
01:02:04,820 --> 01:02:06,068
No.

488
01:02:08,400 --> 01:02:10,313
Well, in ages before history,

489
01:02:10,315 --> 01:02:11,935
this was a holy site

490
01:02:11,937 --> 01:02:13,479
of the ancient Druids.

491
01:02:15,477 --> 01:02:17,391
They worshipped unknown gods.

492
01:02:19,097 --> 01:02:20,596
Worshipped in these woods.

493
01:02:22,178 --> 01:02:24,673
Then the Romans came long ago,
and they sensed

494
01:02:24,675 --> 01:02:26,004
the magic of this place,

495
01:02:26,006 --> 01:02:27,672
so they built their temples.

496
01:02:29,545 --> 01:02:31,334
And people upon people
sensed it,

497
01:02:31,336 --> 01:02:33,334
and they came here to worship.

498
01:02:34,914 --> 01:02:36,661
Countless gods,
tribe after tribe,

499
01:02:36,663 --> 01:02:39,494
who would not even know
how to speak to each other.

500
01:02:40,659 --> 01:02:42,864
Yet we were all
pulled to this place.

501
01:02:44,946 --> 01:02:47,569
Do you believe
there is magic in this island?

502
01:02:50,067 --> 01:02:51,731
I believe there is power
in it.

503
01:02:54,562 --> 01:02:56,768
I have seen
the power in stories.

504
01:02:59,433 --> 01:03:02,720
They can be used to make men
do terrible things.

505
01:03:03,802 --> 01:03:07,757
And then those terrible things
become stories.

506
01:03:09,089 --> 01:03:10,297
And stories...

507
01:03:14,625 --> 01:03:15,624
No.

508
01:03:16,332 --> 01:03:17,829
You cannot trust any of them.

509
01:03:18,828 --> 01:03:20,661
We cannot be
trusted with them.

510
01:03:23,034 --> 01:03:25,821
Knives cut bread
as well as they do flesh.

511
01:03:27,529 --> 01:03:29,194
It's a question of balance.

512
01:03:30,068 --> 01:03:31,774
Does balance
have a say?

513
01:03:34,314 --> 01:03:36,728
I think if balance
did not have some say,

514
01:03:37,934 --> 01:03:39,393
we would not be here.

515
01:03:41,515 --> 01:03:45,345
This world would not...
be here and...

516
01:03:46,676 --> 01:03:48,798
we would not be
sharing these words.

517
01:03:49,965 --> 01:03:51,381
And do you ever consider that?

518
01:03:53,503 --> 01:03:55,208
The incredible precision
of balance

519
01:03:55,210 --> 01:03:57,707
over such an expanse of time.

520
01:03:59,331 --> 01:04:03,574
The balance it takes to create
a word, any specific word.

521
01:04:03,576 --> 01:04:06,407
That can pass
between lips and...

522
01:04:08,239 --> 01:04:10,527
be understood by two minds.

523
01:04:17,937 --> 01:04:19,228
Randolph.

524
01:04:23,140 --> 01:04:24,431
Thank you.

525
01:05:30,032 --> 01:05:31,821
- Mmm. Mmm.
- Mmm.

526
01:05:43,518 --> 01:05:44,558
Not hungry?

527
01:05:46,515 --> 01:05:47,679
No?

528
01:06:20,357 --> 01:06:21,855
I'll be dying soon.

529
01:06:23,686 --> 01:06:24,727
How do you know?

530
01:06:27,141 --> 01:06:29,098
I can
feel it inside.

531
01:06:31,471 --> 01:06:33,302
What does it feel like?

532
01:06:35,425 --> 01:06:37,090
It feels right.

533
01:06:48,661 --> 01:06:50,202
There's someone there.

534
01:06:53,199 --> 01:06:54,822
The waters
have been busy.

535
01:06:58,277 --> 01:06:59,567
Start around the feet.

536
01:07:00,067 --> 01:07:01,274
Little cuts.

537
01:07:01,731 --> 01:07:02,772
Good. Other one.

538
01:07:05,020 --> 01:07:07,268
All right. Oh.

539
01:07:08,933 --> 01:07:10,140
Okay.

540
01:07:11,014 --> 01:07:12,593
Good.

541
01:07:12,595 --> 01:07:14,342
Right, now,
let's do down the front.

542
01:07:14,344 --> 01:07:16,134
Right down on the belly. Good.

543
01:07:17,133 --> 01:07:19,171
Right. Give me.

544
01:07:19,173 --> 01:07:21,127
Right. Watch this one.

545
01:07:21,129 --> 01:07:23,874
Just like... just like that.

546
01:07:23,876 --> 01:07:25,541
That's it.
You do the other one.

547
01:07:26,998 --> 01:07:29,369
That's it, that's it,
that's it.

548
01:07:29,371 --> 01:07:30,370
Pull.

549
01:08:05,834 --> 01:08:08,124
You are a brave
young man.

550
01:08:09,123 --> 01:08:10,456
Thank you, sister.

551
01:08:12,328 --> 01:08:13,701
Are you hungry, Arthur?

552
01:08:17,655 --> 01:08:19,194
I am, sister.

553
01:08:19,196 --> 01:08:21,858
Well, Sarah will fix you up
a good supper tonight.

554
01:08:21,860 --> 01:08:24,233
Herring stew. Herring stew.

555
01:08:26,147 --> 01:08:29,101
-Do you like that?
-Yes.

556
01:08:29,103 --> 01:08:30,517
Where do you come from,
Arthur?

557
01:08:34,348 --> 01:08:36,052
My family farm
toward Keswick.

558
01:08:36,054 --> 01:08:38,217
- Toward Keswick?
- Yes, Sir.

559
01:08:38,219 --> 01:08:41,130
-Randolph
-Randolph. Toward Keswick.

560
01:08:41,132 --> 01:08:43,130
The Leper said
you seek your niece.

561
01:08:44,004 --> 01:08:45,502
-I do.
-You were set upon?

562
01:08:47,917 --> 01:08:49,458
-I was.
-On the road?

563
01:08:51,373 --> 01:08:52,618
Yes.

564
01:08:52,620 --> 01:08:54,370
-You are safe here.
-Which road?

565
01:08:56,242 --> 01:08:57,699
The road to Keswick, Sir.

566
01:08:59,281 --> 01:09:01,027
Thank the Lord you survived.

567
01:09:01,029 --> 01:09:02,402
I do thank the Lord.

568
01:09:02,404 --> 01:09:04,232
How about honeyed pears
after supper

569
01:09:04,234 --> 01:09:05,691
for being so brave?

570
01:09:08,854 --> 01:09:11,102
-Thank you, sister.
-Good.

571
01:09:24,547 --> 01:09:25,796
Little Margaret.

572
01:09:27,170 --> 01:09:28,707
That man, Arthur.

573
01:09:28,709 --> 01:09:31,540
Did you ever see him
before you came to the Priory?

574
01:09:34,787 --> 01:09:35,786
Margaret.

575
01:09:43,321 --> 01:09:46,775
The men...
The men who hurt your papa.

576
01:09:49,647 --> 01:09:51,272
Did you see their faces?

577
01:09:52,560 --> 01:09:54,101
Papa said to run.

578
01:10:04,965 --> 01:10:06,298
Papa stopped praying.

579
01:10:08,087 --> 01:10:09,210
He was angry.

580
01:10:10,834 --> 01:10:12,251
He prayed in his mind.

581
01:10:15,662 --> 01:10:16,661
What's Papa's name?

582
01:10:21,032 --> 01:10:22,365
Your papa's your papa.

583
01:10:35,060 --> 01:10:36,268
Bring it here.

584
01:10:45,841 --> 01:10:47,797
Oh, this is fine work.

585
01:10:51,918 --> 01:10:53,293
Oh.

586
01:10:53,833 --> 01:10:55,581
You see it favors
a bend here.

587
01:10:57,289 --> 01:11:01,034
Oh, aye. Now you have to
balance it so it bends evenly.

588
01:11:01,866 --> 01:11:05,654
So this part here needs
to be thinned. All right?

589
01:11:11,067 --> 01:11:12,522
Can you make for me?

590
01:11:15,395 --> 01:11:16,810
You want me
to make you a bow?

591
01:11:21,555 --> 01:11:22,595
All right.

592
01:11:30,629 --> 01:11:32,169
Today,
I remembered a story

593
01:11:32,171 --> 01:11:34,540
by a poet named Lucretius.

594
01:11:36,499 --> 01:11:38,497
He wrote on
what are called atoms.

595
01:11:40,287 --> 01:11:42,242
Where if you pick apart
the trees

596
01:11:42,244 --> 01:11:44,073
and people and stones,

597
01:11:44,075 --> 01:11:47,527
these would be the smallest
invisible pieces

598
01:11:47,529 --> 01:11:51,110
that make up
everything in creation.

599
01:11:52,983 --> 01:11:57,436
And these atoms are sailing
through the void and...

600
01:12:00,267 --> 01:12:02,097
well, sometimes,
for no reason at all,

601
01:12:02,099 --> 01:12:03,430
they change their course.

602
01:12:06,427 --> 01:12:08,633
The least amount,
not even a hair.

603
01:12:13,503 --> 01:12:17,375
And if it weren't
for that small...

604
01:12:18,208 --> 01:12:22,202
unpredictable change
forcing the atoms to cross

605
01:12:22,204 --> 01:12:24,160
and weave with each other...

606
01:12:27,323 --> 01:12:30,154
nothing at all
under the heavens would exist.

607
01:15:13,949 --> 01:15:15,986
Yes. Good.

608
01:15:15,988 --> 01:15:17,403
Harder.

609
01:15:18,028 --> 01:15:19,316
That's it. Good.

610
01:15:22,648 --> 01:15:24,854
That's good. Harder.

611
01:15:25,770 --> 01:15:27,224
Let me help you.

612
01:15:28,725 --> 01:15:29,724
Grab that one.

613
01:15:31,015 --> 01:15:33,304
Good. There we go!

614
01:15:33,637 --> 01:15:34,676
Good.

615
01:15:38,132 --> 01:15:39,673
Which one do you think
for your bow?

616
01:15:40,547 --> 01:15:41,796
Let's hold and look.

617
01:15:42,753 --> 01:15:43,752
Okay.

618
01:15:44,543 --> 01:15:46,664
There we go.
They're both good.

619
01:15:57,946 --> 01:15:59,692
Margaret!

620
01:15:59,694 --> 01:16:01,315
Margaret! Come and play!

621
01:16:41,694 --> 01:16:42,693
Arthur.

622
01:16:44,066 --> 01:16:45,646
Do you know how to trap?

623
01:16:45,648 --> 01:16:47,353
-Yes.
-Good.

624
01:16:47,355 --> 01:16:49,395
I need a strong hand. Come.

625
01:17:02,506 --> 01:17:04,171
Does your family have land?

626
01:17:05,878 --> 01:17:06,836
Yes.

627
01:17:08,917 --> 01:17:10,333
How many
of you are there?

628
01:17:12,331 --> 01:17:13,579
I don't know.

629
01:17:20,489 --> 01:17:21,737
Are you all right?

630
01:17:23,527 --> 01:17:25,148
I am. I am.

631
01:17:25,150 --> 01:17:27,148
Just not as young
as I once were.

632
01:17:29,813 --> 01:17:31,395
I could use a hand up is all.

633
01:17:36,222 --> 01:17:37,431
Thank you.

634
01:17:39,053 --> 01:17:41,092
Oh aye, they delivered you
quite a blow.

635
01:17:43,090 --> 01:17:44,340
-Yes.
-Who did it?

636
01:17:47,003 --> 01:17:48,253
A man.

637
01:17:48,710 --> 01:17:49,751
Some men.

638
01:17:50,957 --> 01:17:52,831
-Bandits.
-A man, bandits?

639
01:17:53,954 --> 01:17:55,620
-Yes.
-Huh. May I look?

640
01:18:01,739 --> 01:18:03,610
It's quite a blow.

641
01:18:03,612 --> 01:18:07,106
Oh, you're lucky you survived.
You're a lucky boy.

642
01:18:07,108 --> 01:18:08,188
Yes.

643
01:18:08,190 --> 01:18:10,479
You should be thankful
to be alive.

644
01:18:10,481 --> 01:18:12,770
-Yes.
-He used a quarterstaff?

645
01:18:19,054 --> 01:18:20,427
Hmm.

646
01:18:20,429 --> 01:18:22,344
Lucky it didn't
take your head off.

647
01:18:27,088 --> 01:18:28,754
Randolph.

648
01:18:31,501 --> 01:18:32,750
Randolph.

649
01:18:35,788 --> 01:18:36,829
Moshe?

650
01:18:40,409 --> 01:18:43,114
The Prioress said to come.

651
01:19:24,573 --> 01:19:26,779
Are you in great pain?

652
01:19:35,936 --> 01:19:37,809
Do you remember the trees?

653
01:19:40,433 --> 01:19:42,431
Pears, apples
and elderberries.

654
01:19:45,010 --> 01:19:46,260
Wonderful.

655
01:19:56,666 --> 01:19:59,868
You know that you are
the most important person

656
01:19:59,870 --> 01:20:01,661
in Little Margaret's life.

657
01:20:02,244 --> 01:20:05,199
Ah, I'm not important.

658
01:20:17,852 --> 01:20:19,433
Think of all the people

659
01:20:19,435 --> 01:20:21,350
whose lives you've crossed.

660
01:20:24,513 --> 01:20:27,302
We were important somehow
to all of them.

661
01:20:34,711 --> 01:20:37,832
Do you know the story
of Guy of Gisborne

662
01:20:39,998 --> 01:20:41,537
and Robin Hood?

663
01:20:46,781 --> 01:20:48,073
Yes.

664
01:20:52,901 --> 01:20:55,233
They say you killed him.

665
01:20:57,189 --> 01:20:58,726
Did you really behead him?

666
01:20:58,728 --> 01:21:02,101
-You are confused, leper.
-Well, I'll not tell a soul.

667
01:21:04,639 --> 01:21:07,636
But don't lie to a man
on his deathbed.

668
01:21:10,218 --> 01:21:13,796
So, did you really behead him?

669
01:21:17,336 --> 01:21:19,664
There were no Guy of Gisborne.

670
01:21:19,666 --> 01:21:22,745
It were just one of the many
tales that passed along.

671
01:21:25,119 --> 01:21:26,700
But I beheaded other men.

672
01:21:34,402 --> 01:21:36,400
You really don't remember?

673
01:21:38,939 --> 01:21:41,226
No.

674
01:21:41,228 --> 01:21:42,767
Think about that name.

675
01:21:47,431 --> 01:21:49,803
There were a Guy of Gisborne.

676
01:21:53,756 --> 01:21:55,464
But you did not behead him.

677
01:21:58,211 --> 01:21:59,626
You cut off his ear.

678
01:22:07,452 --> 01:22:12,528
You said, in another life,
you'd share a drink with him.

679
01:22:14,861 --> 01:22:16,235
Do you remember that?

680
01:22:28,265 --> 01:22:31,470
We seem to have
found another life.

681
01:22:38,421 --> 01:22:41,333
Now,
there is one cruelty

682
01:22:41,335 --> 01:22:43,913
I would ask you
to not bring about.

683
01:22:46,330 --> 01:22:48,368
You will
guard the orchard

684
01:22:48,370 --> 01:22:50,616
until you too die.

685
01:22:53,822 --> 01:22:56,070
You will serve the Prioress...

686
01:22:57,568 --> 01:23:01,190
and the people of this Priory,
past and future.

687
01:23:05,977 --> 01:23:09,681
But at no point
in that time...

688
01:23:12,387 --> 01:23:16,632
in those
good and peaceful years,

689
01:23:19,671 --> 01:23:23,083
will you tell the Prioress
who you really are.

690
01:23:29,578 --> 01:23:30,618
Why?

691
01:23:33,033 --> 01:23:34,282
Because...

692
01:23:36,072 --> 01:23:38,068
one of those nameless,

693
01:23:38,070 --> 01:23:39,358
faceless deaths

694
01:23:39,360 --> 01:23:41,400
in the shadows of your mind...

695
01:23:44,355 --> 01:23:46,103
were in another life...

696
01:23:48,934 --> 01:23:50,349
her beloved.

697
01:23:58,799 --> 01:23:59,839
Promise me.

698
01:24:05,126 --> 01:24:06,333
Robin...

699
01:24:08,081 --> 01:24:09,330
Promise me.

700
01:24:36,636 --> 01:24:44,168
♪ Sumer is icumen in
Loude sing cuccu! ♪

701
01:24:44,170 --> 01:24:47,374
♪ Groweth seed
and bloweth meed ♪

702
01:24:47,376 --> 01:24:51,036
♪ And springth the wode now ♪

703
01:24:51,038 --> 01:24:54,657
♪ Sing cuccu ♪

704
01:24:54,659 --> 01:25:01,110
♪ Ewe bleteth after lamb
Loweth after calve cow ♪

705
01:25:01,112 --> 01:25:04,939
♪ Bulloc sterteth
bucke verteth ♪

706
01:25:04,941 --> 01:25:07,811
♪ Merye sing cuccu! ♪

707
01:25:07,813 --> 01:25:14,389
♪ Cuccu, cuccu
Wel singest thou cuccu! ♪

708
01:25:14,391 --> 01:25:16,429
♪ Ne swik thou never now! ♪

709
01:25:41,197 --> 01:25:42,570
Good-bye, Brigid.

710
01:25:56,098 --> 01:25:57,264
Arthur.

711
01:25:59,636 --> 01:26:00,718
Come.

712
01:26:03,882 --> 01:26:05,630
There's a child
on the far shore.

713
01:26:07,255 --> 01:26:08,627
Perhaps it's your niece.

714
01:26:10,708 --> 01:26:12,831
The Leper said
you sought your lost niece.

715
01:26:14,621 --> 01:26:16,369
Yes.

716
01:26:16,371 --> 01:26:18,825
-Could it be her?
-We shall see.

717
01:26:58,162 --> 01:27:00,160
I do not see signs of anyone.

718
01:27:01,367 --> 01:27:02,698
Ah, we should wait.

719
01:27:03,697 --> 01:27:05,113
Maybe they will return.

720
01:27:27,300 --> 01:27:28,547
What is your name?

721
01:27:32,710 --> 01:27:33,792
Arthur.

722
01:27:35,125 --> 01:27:37,246
Do not waste time lying to me.

723
01:27:37,248 --> 01:27:38,496
What is your real name?

724
01:27:43,450 --> 01:27:44,531
Godwyn.

725
01:27:47,820 --> 01:27:50,233
You are deciding, Godwyn,

726
01:27:50,235 --> 01:27:52,399
whether to do
the deed yourself...

727
01:27:53,689 --> 01:27:55,189
or to fetch your family.

728
01:27:58,600 --> 01:27:59,556
What deed?

729
01:27:59,558 --> 01:28:01,722
How many men
have you killed, Godwyn?

730
01:28:03,222 --> 01:28:05,966
How many children
have you killed?

731
01:28:11,338 --> 01:28:14,419
I have killed so many,
I could not give you a count.

732
01:28:16,168 --> 01:28:18,039
For longer than
you've been alive.

733
01:28:18,041 --> 01:28:21,036
I've been killing the kin of
those I killed a lifetime ago.

734
01:28:21,038 --> 01:28:23,075
I do not remember the first,

735
01:28:23,077 --> 01:28:25,366
who meant nothing to me
at the time, but...

736
01:28:26,614 --> 01:28:28,652
their brothers
and their children,

737
01:28:28,654 --> 01:28:31,277
their grandchildren,
they remember me.

738
01:28:32,235 --> 01:28:34,274
So now I must kill them.

739
01:28:35,232 --> 01:28:37,768
Again and again.

740
01:28:37,770 --> 01:28:41,766
In different forms,
like shades. Again.

741
01:28:43,141 --> 01:28:45,304
And again,
and it never ceases.

742
01:28:48,925 --> 01:28:50,632
It's a curse, Godwyn.

743
01:28:52,464 --> 01:28:54,128
And it's one
you bring on yourself,

744
01:28:54,130 --> 01:28:56,834
even if done through duty.

745
01:28:57,833 --> 01:28:59,831
It cares not about your duty.

746
01:29:00,622 --> 01:29:03,619
This world cares
only about blood.

747
01:29:05,368 --> 01:29:07,573
And blood is all
it will give in return.

748
01:29:10,279 --> 01:29:13,235
But do you want
to kill a child, Godwyn?

749
01:29:15,523 --> 01:29:17,146
Do you want to be responsible

750
01:29:17,148 --> 01:29:19,561
for the killing
of a little girl?

751
01:29:22,976 --> 01:29:24,183
No.

752
01:29:36,004 --> 01:29:37,501
Your father's dead?

753
01:29:39,085 --> 01:29:40,165
And your uncles?

754
01:29:43,330 --> 01:29:45,079
I am the eldest left.

755
01:29:49,739 --> 01:29:51,114
Who else yet lives, Godwyn?

756
01:29:53,652 --> 01:29:54,734
My mother.

757
01:29:56,524 --> 01:29:57,565
My aunts.

758
01:29:59,065 --> 01:30:00,685
My sisters.

759
01:30:00,687 --> 01:30:02,601
You have a home, Godwyn?

760
01:30:04,934 --> 01:30:06,681
-Yes.
-Go home.

761
01:30:08,014 --> 01:30:10,635
Tell your family
all blood debts are paid.

762
01:30:11,343 --> 01:30:13,134
They'll all be paid someday.

763
01:30:15,339 --> 01:30:16,671
Sleep in your own bed.

764
01:30:17,962 --> 01:30:20,125
Hold dear the life

765
01:30:20,127 --> 01:30:22,249
you will yet share
with your kin.

766
01:30:23,831 --> 01:30:25,537
And if you return here,

767
01:30:26,661 --> 01:30:28,241
you will have wasted
this chance

768
01:30:28,243 --> 01:30:30,158
at life that I give you now.

769
01:30:31,948 --> 01:30:33,819
And I will cut your throat

770
01:30:33,821 --> 01:30:35,568
and never think of you again.

771
01:30:42,437 --> 01:30:43,478
Go now.

772
01:30:45,976 --> 01:30:47,266
And do not look back.

773
01:31:41,878 --> 01:31:44,165
I thought
you had departed.

774
01:31:53,866 --> 01:31:55,364
I am Robin the Outlaw.

775
01:31:59,069 --> 01:32:02,732
You... You need to know
that I'm a monster.

776
01:32:05,063 --> 01:32:06,519
I'm not one Randolph.

777
01:32:09,267 --> 01:32:12,513
I am the outlaw, Robin Hood.

778
01:32:27,082 --> 01:32:29,247
I'm sorry...

779
01:34:29,378 --> 01:34:30,834
Tell me I should leave.

780
01:34:33,665 --> 01:34:34,705
I will go now.

781
01:34:42,864 --> 01:34:44,154
Get in the bed.

782
01:35:04,092 --> 01:35:05,799
-Brigid...
-Lie down.

783
01:38:31,303 --> 01:38:33,550
You burned my husband alive.

784
01:38:39,045 --> 01:38:40,541
I dream that
he was already dead,

785
01:38:40,543 --> 01:38:43,291
but why else did you bar
the door?

786
01:38:47,869 --> 01:38:49,241
It felt like a lifetime

787
01:38:49,243 --> 01:38:51,782
searching the ashes
of our home.

788
01:38:55,112 --> 01:38:56,818
And he looked so small.

789
01:38:58,816 --> 01:39:02,645
Curled up in the corner
with so much of him gone.

790
01:39:07,308 --> 01:39:08,804
But as much as I dream,

791
01:39:08,806 --> 01:39:10,305
I know he was alive.

792
01:39:15,009 --> 01:39:16,838
Because, until the very end,

793
01:39:16,840 --> 01:39:18,295
he had wrapped himself

794
01:39:18,297 --> 01:39:20,337
around our children.

795
01:40:07,831 --> 01:40:09,745
Randolph...

796
01:40:11,827 --> 01:40:13,076
...it's me.

797
01:41:07,147 --> 01:41:09,311
People speak
of Robin Hood.

798
01:41:14,265 --> 01:41:15,846
Tell his stories.

799
01:41:22,215 --> 01:41:23,755
They're all lies.

800
01:41:27,751 --> 01:41:30,458
Lies that I told long ago.

801
01:41:32,122 --> 01:41:33,703
So that fools would...

802
01:41:35,244 --> 01:41:37,325
follow me into the dark.

803
01:41:46,857 --> 01:41:49,604
Robin.

804
01:41:54,434 --> 01:41:56,348
What have they done to you?

805
01:42:02,258 --> 01:42:04,131
Don't be afraid.

806
01:42:06,129 --> 01:42:08,793
I will rescue you
from this place.

807
01:42:10,874 --> 01:42:13,164
I'll rescue Little Margaret.

808
01:42:14,704 --> 01:42:17,867
And we're gonna start
a new life together.

809
01:42:18,575 --> 01:42:19,615
Edward...

810
01:42:23,986 --> 01:42:26,193
tell me about your wife.

811
01:42:35,933 --> 01:42:37,140
My wife.

812
01:42:39,929 --> 01:42:41,136
Margaret.

813
01:42:45,257 --> 01:42:46,464
Margaret.

814
01:42:48,836 --> 01:42:50,751
My wife, Margaret.

815
01:42:53,041 --> 01:42:54,622
Paint a portrait.

816
01:42:57,203 --> 01:42:58,576
Paint a portrait?

817
01:43:02,989 --> 01:43:04,405
She has hair...

818
01:43:06,652 --> 01:43:07,776
red like...

819
01:43:09,565 --> 01:43:11,439
the setting sun.

820
01:43:14,271 --> 01:43:17,516
Like the setting summer sun.

821
01:43:24,800 --> 01:43:25,799
Red like...

822
01:43:26,673 --> 01:43:28,838
the setting summer...

823
01:43:29,920 --> 01:43:31,212
sun.

824
01:43:49,401 --> 01:43:50,400
Robin...

825
01:43:56,478 --> 01:43:58,766
Have you found
your right death?

826
01:44:59,498 --> 01:45:01,537
I'm ready to finish it.

827
01:45:08,696 --> 01:45:10,445
I owe this life to you.

828
01:45:18,230 --> 01:45:19,727
It is monstrous.

829
01:45:24,224 --> 01:45:26,222
But I owe this life to you.

830
01:45:26,928 --> 01:45:28,510
You owe me nothing.

831
01:45:33,922 --> 01:45:36,212
I have never taken
a life before.

832
01:45:37,709 --> 01:45:38,708
Ah.

833
01:45:40,457 --> 01:45:43,122
It can be
as if pruning a flower.

834
01:45:45,036 --> 01:45:46,781
Well, it should not be.

835
01:45:46,783 --> 01:45:49,116
Aye, it should not.

836
01:45:50,738 --> 01:45:51,862
But it can.

837
01:45:57,647 --> 01:46:00,270
I help those
who come to this island.

838
01:46:03,060 --> 01:46:04,308
I heal them.

839
01:46:08,429 --> 01:46:09,470
Please.

840
01:46:14,965 --> 01:46:16,379
Heal me.

841
01:47:12,033 --> 01:47:13,571
Little Margaret...

842
01:47:19,358 --> 01:47:21,647
your father's name were John.

843
01:47:31,097 --> 01:47:33,219
I knew him for many years.

844
01:47:34,385 --> 01:47:36,548
Before he were your papa.

845
01:47:42,542 --> 01:47:43,667
I met him...

846
01:47:45,290 --> 01:47:47,372
crossing a bridge one day...

847
01:47:48,954 --> 01:47:51,201
over a rushing river.

848
01:47:53,741 --> 01:47:55,197
He was stubborn.

849
01:47:58,236 --> 01:48:00,648
He would not yield.

850
01:48:00,650 --> 01:48:03,772
Oh, not to any man.

851
01:48:05,270 --> 01:48:06,686
Not even to me.

852
01:48:10,099 --> 01:48:11,597
So we wrestled.

853
01:48:12,554 --> 01:48:13,721
On that bridge.

854
01:48:15,927 --> 01:48:19,131
Striking. Back and forth.

855
01:48:21,171 --> 01:48:23,627
I whacked him
on the side of the head.

856
01:48:26,166 --> 01:48:28,331
He struck me in the stomach.

857
01:48:29,830 --> 01:48:32,118
And I wobbled on that bridge.

858
01:48:33,867 --> 01:48:35,115
Splash!

859
01:48:36,364 --> 01:48:38,571
He knocked me on me bum.

860
01:48:42,442 --> 01:48:44,565
Once I dragged myself out,

861
01:48:45,689 --> 01:48:47,270
drenched to the bone,

862
01:48:49,060 --> 01:48:50,267
we embraced.

863
01:48:53,931 --> 01:48:55,511
We called your papa...

864
01:48:56,553 --> 01:48:57,635
Little John.

865
01:48:59,216 --> 01:49:01,381
And we lived for many years...

866
01:49:04,753 --> 01:49:08,207
as outlaws in the greenwood.

867
01:49:11,163 --> 01:49:12,787
Oh, we had feasts.

868
01:49:14,368 --> 01:49:15,367
We...

869
01:49:15,950 --> 01:49:17,365
We gave silver...

870
01:49:18,531 --> 01:49:19,571
to the meek.

871
01:49:24,150 --> 01:49:25,690
No...

872
01:49:36,846 --> 01:49:39,135
But we stole that silver.

873
01:49:44,880 --> 01:49:46,128
We stole it...

874
01:49:47,793 --> 01:49:51,081
from, from bad people.

875
01:49:55,869 --> 01:49:57,117
You understand?

876
01:49:59,698 --> 01:50:00,739
Bad people.

877
01:50:16,139 --> 01:50:17,389
Your papa...

878
01:50:18,887 --> 01:50:20,635
would want me to tell you...

879
01:50:26,629 --> 01:50:29,377
because he loved you
so dearly.

880
01:50:33,122 --> 01:50:35,579
You must never tell a soul.

881
01:50:37,118 --> 01:50:39,492
Not even the children
you play with.

882
01:50:41,156 --> 01:50:44,778
You must never tell them
your papa's name.

883
01:50:49,023 --> 01:50:51,104
There are
bad people out there.

884
01:50:53,935 --> 01:50:57,598
And they are angry
with your papa.

885
01:51:01,968 --> 01:51:04,048
And so they're angry with you.

886
01:51:09,086 --> 01:51:11,460
And can we keep that secret?

887
01:51:13,582 --> 01:51:16,372
I can keep that secret,
Little Margaret.

888
01:51:18,869 --> 01:51:20,117
Can you?

889
01:51:24,696 --> 01:51:26,237
Good.

890
01:51:28,192 --> 01:51:29,691
Now come beside me.

891
01:51:39,889 --> 01:51:41,138
Take this.

892
01:51:43,052 --> 01:51:44,386
Why were he "Little"?

893
01:51:45,634 --> 01:51:46,633
What?

894
01:51:47,798 --> 01:51:49,960
Why were my papa
called "Little"?

895
01:51:55,540 --> 01:51:58,121
Because he were little
when I found him.

896
01:51:59,910 --> 01:52:01,032
Like you.

897
01:52:09,152 --> 01:52:10,401
String it.

898
01:52:33,544 --> 01:52:36,708
Bend it with your leg
as you saw me do.

899
01:52:53,566 --> 01:52:54,565
Good.

900
01:52:56,105 --> 01:52:59,850
Now, go to the window.

901
01:53:20,622 --> 01:53:21,663
Now,

902
01:53:23,744 --> 01:53:24,784
nock an arrow.

903
01:53:33,651 --> 01:53:34,857
Find a point

904
01:53:36,065 --> 01:53:38,438
where the waters meet the sky.

905
01:53:43,475 --> 01:53:45,722
Pull that arrow to your mouth.

906
01:53:49,842 --> 01:53:51,134
And hold.

907
01:53:52,965 --> 01:53:55,088
I will tell you when to loose.

908
01:53:58,085 --> 01:53:59,500
And when I do...

909
01:54:00,665 --> 01:54:02,164
you're not letting go.

910
01:54:05,036 --> 01:54:07,368
You're simply
not holding on anymore.

911
01:54:12,404 --> 01:54:13,403
Now.

912
01:54:14,943 --> 01:54:16,442
Watch that target.

913
01:54:19,563 --> 01:54:22,103
Your body
will always be moving.

914
01:54:25,141 --> 01:54:29,636
Feel when that arrow
will fly true.

915
01:54:32,967 --> 01:54:35,173
You're gonna find a dance.

916
01:54:37,338 --> 01:54:39,835
Hold until I tell you
to loose.

917
01:54:43,581 --> 01:54:45,205
You are strong.

918
01:54:46,162 --> 01:54:47,742
Feel...

919
01:54:49,533 --> 01:54:50,781
that sway,

920
01:54:54,487 --> 01:54:55,569
that dance.

921
01:55:02,769 --> 01:55:04,267
Now loose.